[4] Cholera - Uganda (Kampala)
Date: Mon, 18 Dec 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and New Vision (Kampala) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200612180254.html>

The number of cholera cases has increased since the 1st case was
reported 3 months ago. Kampala, which is the most strongly hit by the
epidemic, has registered 553 patients from 463. The death toll rose
to 8 on Fri morning, 15 Dec 2006, after a child was reported dead at
the Mulago cholera treatment center.
Winnie Bukenya, a senior midwife at the center, said the epidemic was
due to the poor sanitation in the slums. She said the number of
admissions have been higher than discharges.
"The slum dwellers build next to trenches and once their latrines are
full, they are unblocked into the trenches meant to transport rain
water. This causes the spread of the bacteria," Bukenya said.
A statement from the Ministry of Health identified the worst hit
areas as Bwaise, Kalerwe, Nsoba, Mulago, Katwe, Mengo, Kisenyi,
Namuwongo, Luzira and Katanga, all city suburbs. It is said the most
affected areas are located close to the wetlands. The statement said
the heavy rains and increased movement during Christmas season are
likely to worsen the current Cholera situation.
Cholera cases have continued to be reported in the districts of
Kitgum, Pader, Kasese, Bundibugyo, Hoima, Arua, Yumbe and Koboko.
--
