[6] Cholera - Tanzania (Dar es Salaam)
Date: Mon, 18 Dec 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: IRIN [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/2b1a7e04b2625fc21e64901c5fb5c2b7.htm>

Health authorities in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania's commercial capital,
have started distributing chlorine to purify water in wells, in a bid
to control cholera, which continues to wreak havoc in the city.
"The chemical has been distributed to all 3 municipalities of Dar es
Salaam and should be applied in wells 3 times a day," Deogratius
Mutasiwa, the Dar es Salaam City Medical Officer, told IRIN.
He said chlorine had no side effects; it was also being used to
purify piped water. Mutasiwa said health centers in the city had
continued to record new cholera cases although the rate had declined
significantly, with a daily average of 17 since the beginning of Dec
2006.
"Compared to the past, there is some improvement," he said. "In Oct
2006, we had an average of 50 cases a day."
Dar es Salaam Regional Commissioner Abbas Kandoro said from 12 Dec
2005 to 20 Nov 2006, 11 227 people had contracted cholera in the
region, 117 of whom had died.
--
